03795nam a22005295i 9780889206526DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061975xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892065267 a10.51644/97808892065262doi  a(DE-B1597)667627  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBS1192.6 7aREL0060902bisacsh04a296.311  aBC 68302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9593:1 aParke-Taylor, G.H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYahweh :bThe Divine Name in the Bible /cG.H. Parke-Taylor. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1975  a1 online resource (144 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tTable Of Contents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tThe Name Of God -- tThe Tetragrammaton Before Moses -- tThe God Of The Fathers -- tThe God Of Moses -- tThe Tetragrammaton in the old Testament -- tThe Tetragrammaton Within Judaism -- tThe Tetragrammaton Within Christianity -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex Of Biblical References -- tIndex Of Authors -- tIndex Of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBiblical tradition asserts that the revelation of God to Moses in the burning bush involved also a declaration of the divine name, the Tet (represented by the letters Y, H, W, H), and its meaning. There are indications that the divine name was known prior to the time of Moses, although ultimate questions of origin and precise meaning are shrouded in obscurity. IN fact, even the exact pronunciation of the name (usually pronounced YAHWEH) is by no means certain. The author of The Divine Name in the Bible surveys the immense literature on this subject, and traces the use of various names for deity in Israel from patriarchal times onwards, with special attention to the significance of the Tetragrammaton, which in course of time, became the name by which the God of Israel was known. Various aspects of the theological meaning of the name in the Old Testament writings are explored. The Dead Sea Scrolls, the Jewish Talmudic literature, and later mystical writings are also examined. The translators of the Old Testament into Greek used Kyrios as the equivalent for YHWH—with implications for the New Testament understanding of the person of Jesus Christ, reflected also in subsequent Christological formulations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGodxNamexBiblical teaching. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920652640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889206526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889206526/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles